          "body": "The theological backbone of the prayer is Deuteronomy 28-30. Nehemiah does not invent his prayer — he researches it. He knows that the scattering of Israel was not a geopolitical accident but a covenant judgment Moses predicted: 'If you are unfaithful I will scatter you among the peoples' (1:8, citing Deuteronomy 28:64). He knows equally that the covenant also promised gathering: 'if you return to Me and keep My commandments...I will gather them' (1:9, citing Deuteronomy 30:1-4). Both poles of the covenant are live for Nehemiah. This means the crisis in Jerusalem is not evidence that God has abandoned Israel — it is evidence that the covenant is working exactly as designed. Judgment came because the covenant warned of judgment. The same covenant now promises restoration if the people return. Nehemiah's prayer does not ask God to make an exception; it asks God to fulfill His word. That is a different kind of prayer, and it is a much stronger one."
